			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">You have to remember, this argument takes place in a courtroom. Every argument you've ever had in your life with anyone wouldn't stand up to ten seconds of legal scrutiny because the rules of engagement there are radically different and very complicated, and have @#%$ all to do with feelings, beliefs, instincts, and assumptions (the cornerstone of most arguments).
<br />

<br />
Blizzard is using the standard "throw everything and the kitchen sink at them and see what sticks" method. Blizzard's lawyers don't exactly know how to approach this, because there is no real precedent, and so they will claim everything and the world and then let the judge himself tell them what does and does not stick. This is a sound legal strategy. They will then use what they get from the judge as the weapons to win the case. I guarantee you they have been planning this legal defense since before the game was out of alpha, having watched what happened to other MMOs.
<br />

<br />
One thing does remain very clear here. 1) Blizzard owns everything that has anything to do with the data on their servers, EULA or no EULA. This is basic property ownership, something courts understand VERY well. 2) People other than Blizzard are making money trading property that does not belong to them, existing only inside Blizzard's servers (property). This is another thing the courts understand very well. Regardless of the details, Blizzard is definitely going to win any lawsuits against Yantis-like activity.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=6290" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/images/smiles/protest.gif" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
