			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, on one hand, I hope Blizzard wins against the Yantis-like companies, as I despise them and what they've done to the games they dip their hands in.
<br />

<br />
On the other hand, I'm not really a big fan of the "throw everything and the kitchen sink at the defendant" approach that most plaintiffs use.  Like I said in my previous post, I think the plaintiffs should be required to ask themselves what claims are actually valid, and stick to those.  Give a judge the power to throw out a case entirely if they're making all kinds of nonsensical claims.  The plaintiff could then re-file the complaint with a narrower scope, but the plaintiff is essentially out any court costs from the first attempt and any legal fees + time spent waiting for a court date... and possibly now the statute of limitations on some of their claims has passed.  So, more of an incentive for them to stick to claims they can at least back up.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
