			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Blizzard may "win," but they won't win.  Just like the record industry "wins" its suits sometimes, but they really just end up spending money for nothing, because they've failed to stem the piracy they want to defeat.  These auction sites really require little to nothing to set up, just like P2P hosts.  Some reports state that this auction activity generates many billions of dollars a year.  With that kind of money floating around, you can bet people are willing to take the risk.  Any victory Vivendi wins will be phyrric and hollow.  If only these companies could find a way to endorse and profit from this type of stuff, it wouldn't be a big deal.  
<br />

<br />
I'm almost certain online item auctions benefit these games more than hurt them.  I have yet to see any company compile a definitive report on how they lose out by letting gamers transfer "ownership" of their items for real money.  They probably don't, but they just can't come up with a way to promote this without mass indignation on the part of the player base.  Just like the record industry can't seem to find a way to make online distribution work for them.  They fear what they can't control and use their dollars and lawyers instead of their brains to "remedy" the problem.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
