			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I wouldn't be totally against a company setting up their own shop to compete with the "black market" sites.  I don't like the idea of in-game market translating to an out-of-game market... but I think we can all take a lesson from Prohibition <img src="images/smiles/razz.gif" alt="razz" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Thing is, I think this wouldn't work too well for most game companies I know.  Those that ebay for a living tend to be the ones that dupe, afkmacro, exploit -- and also killsteal, ninja, scam, and otherwise grief anyone that gets in the way of their farming.  At least as it stands now, a game company (who gave a crap) would be inclined to take action against that farmer.  Even if they don't take action because of his farming/ebaying, they'd take action based on his exploiting or his griefing of other players.
<br />

<br />
Under a dev-sponsored sale system, the game co's would be too tempted to treat frequent auction sellers like preferred customers.  Imagine, you get that named ks'd, or you get that rare drop ninjaed while your group is rolling for it... and a GM pops in and says *you* gotta leave the camp.
<br />

<br />
SOE a while back asked the question on a login poll about whether players would support a SOE-sponsored auction system.  Thing is, with those kinds of polls you can only answer Yes or No.
<br />
My answer is yes, but ONLY IF the game company doing it institutes some measures that are designed to help ensure they don't show bias in favor of frequent sellers.
<br />

<br />
My idea of a few such measures they could implement:
<br />

<br />

<br />
<ul>- Only characters can be sold, not individual items.  This way, you don't go repeatedly farming item x and selling it (at least using the devs' system you don't) -- if you wanna sell item x, you're gonna have to level up a character to put that item x on and sell him/her with it.
<br />

<br />
- Accounts are not sold -- only characters on the account.  After the sale, the characters are moved from one account to the other.  This helps keep clear the ownership of a particular account which can help the game company clearly know who it is (or should be) dealing with when referencing a specific account.  It also makes the seller/buyer restrictions (described below) possible.
<br />
[Since SOE station accounts can be used in more than one game, selling accounts kinda wouldn't even be an option for an SOE game.]
<br />
[This, however, can pose an issue if the seller account has some expansions that the buyer account doesn't have.  I won't attempt to resolve that issue here.]
<br />

<br />
- A given seller account can make only up to 2 sales in a given 12-month period.  This prevents a particular character from being known as a frequent seller and receiving preferential treatment.  Also, the seller cannot have received any negative soulmarks in the past 6 months.  The seller might be able to auction multiple characters within a single sale, but there should be a limit on the number of chars.  (I'll leave it up to others to define that number)
<br />

<br />
- The seller account must have been actively subscribed to the game for the past 3 consecutive months with no breaks in billing (prevents auction shops from downing an account until it's ready for sale), and the current billing must be from a credit card not a game card.  The credit card and contact information must have remained the same for 3 months prior to sale.
<br />

<br />
- A buyer account must be out of its free trial period and actively subscribed with a credit card, not a game card.  It cannot have received any negative soulmarks in the past 3 months.  (If you can't tell, I think it is important to have some form of verifiable identification for the buyer and seller.)
<br />

<br />
- Guides and lower-tier GM's **DO NOT HAVE ACCESS TO SEE AN ACCOUNT'S SALE HISTORY**.  This is absolutely important to help make sure customer service issues are resolved and rules enforced without bias.  If the account bought character(s) within the past month or two, GM's might have access to see that so that they can resolve any issues the buyer raises.  I don't see any reason the seller would petition about characters he/she no longer has, so no access to sale history.
<br />

<br />
- While a character is up for auction, the server places a lock on that character preventing his login.  Other characters that aren't being sold can be logged onto, but not the character(s) for sale.  I would assume that an auction system would allow potential buyers to see a magelo-like profile of the character, and it's important to make sure the seller can't logon at the last minute and move all his stuff to a mule, leaving the buyer with a lesser-equipped toon than what he bid for.
<br />
</ul></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
